# 3D Asset Complexity Analyzer
### Mesh Statistics and Rendering Performance Prediction

> A machine learning pipeline that extracts structural features from 3D assets, benchmarks their rendering performance in Blender, and trains predictive models to forecast render time from mesh complexity metrics.

---

## Overview

This project addresses a core challenge in 3D production pipelines: **predicting how long an asset will take to render before it enters the queue.** By extracting quantifiable mesh statistics — polygon count, texture memory, material complexity, UV maps — and correlating them with measured render times, we train regression and classification models that can estimate rendering cost from asset structure alone.

The tool provides:
- Automated feature extraction from GLTF, GLB, FBX, OBJ, and PLY files
- Blender-based render time benchmarking under standardized settings
- Machine learning models for regression (render time prediction), classification (complexity tier), and clustering (asset grouping)
- Interactive analytics dashboards showing trade-offs between mesh fidelity and performance

---

## Project Structure

```
3d-asset-complexity-analyzer/
│
├── data/
│   ├── demo/                        # Raw 3D asset folders (GLTF/GLB/FBX)
│   ├── features.csv                 # Extracted mesh statistics
│   ├── render_times.csv             # Blender render time labels
│   └── dataset.csv                  # Merged final dataset
│
├── scripts/
│   ├── feature_extractor.py         # Extracts mesh stats from GLTF/GLB/FBX/OBJ/PLY
│   ├── blender_extractor.py         # Extracts Blender-specific features from .blend files
│   ├── blender_render_timer.py      # Imports assets into Blender, renders, records time
│   └── run_pipeline.ps1             # Full automation pipeline (Windows PowerShell)
│
├── notebooks/
│   └── analysis.ipynb               # EDA, ML training, SHAP analysis, dashboards
│
├── models/
│   └── (trained model artifacts)
│
├── requirements.txt
└── README.md
```

---

## Quickstart

### 1. Clone the repository

```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/3d-asset-complexity-analyzer.git
cd 3d-asset-complexity-analyzer
```

### 2. Install dependencies

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 3. Add your 3D assets

Place asset folders inside `data/demo/`. Each asset should follow the standard Sketchfab structure:

```
data/demo/
    my_asset/
        scene.gltf
        scene.bin
        textures/
            diffuse.png
            normal.png
```

### 4. Run the full pipeline (Windows)

```powershell
PowerShell -ExecutionPolicy Bypass -File scripts/run_pipeline.ps1
```

This will:
- Extract mesh features from all assets → `data/features.csv`
- Render each asset in Blender and record time → `data/render_times.csv`
- Merge into a single labeled dataset → `data/dataset.csv`

### 5. Run the notebook

Open `notebooks/analysis.ipynb` in Jupyter or VS Code to train models and explore results.

---

## Feature Extraction

`feature_extractor.py` processes GLTF, GLB, FBX, OBJ, and PLY files using `trimesh` and `Pillow`.

**Extracted features:**

| Category | Features |
|---|---|
| Geometry | `vertex_count`, `face_count`, `edge_count`, `surface_area`, `bounding_box_volume` |
| Density | `vertex_density`, `polygon_density`, `bbox_x`, `bbox_y`, `bbox_z` |
| Topology | `is_watertight`, `is_winding_consistent`, `euler_number`, `duplicate_faces`, `degenerate_faces` |
| Textures | `texture_count`, `total_texture_pixels`, `total_texture_memory_mb`, `max_texture_width`, `max_texture_height`, `has_normal_map`, `has_displacement_map` |
| Materials | `material_count` |
| File | `file_name`, `file_format`, `file_size_mb` |
| Label | `complexity_tier` (low / mid / high / extreme) |

**Run manually on a folder:**

```bash
python scripts/feature_extractor.py \
  --input data/demo \
  --output data/features.csv \
  --recursive \
  --summary
```

**Run on a single file:**

```bash
python scripts/feature_extractor.py \
  --input data/demo/911/scene.gltf \
  --output data/features.csv
```

---

## Blender Render Timing

`blender_render_timer.py` is called by the pipeline for each asset. It opens Blender headlessly, imports the asset, enforces standardized render settings, renders one frame, and records the wall-clock time.

**Fixed render settings applied to every asset:**

| Setting | Value |
|---|---|
| Engine | Cycles |
| Device | CPU |
| Samples | 128 |
| Max bounces | 12 |
| Denoising | On |
| Resolution | 1920 × 1080 |

> All assets must be rendered on the **same machine** under the same settings. Render time labels are hardware-specific — a model trained on one machine's measurements will predict times for that machine only.

**Run manually on one asset:**

```bash
blender --background --python scripts/blender_render_timer.py \
  -- --input data/demo/911/scene.gltf --output data/render_times.csv
```

---

## Machine Learning Models

Three families of models are trained and evaluated:

**Regression** — predicts continuous render time (seconds)
- Linear Regression (interpretable baseline)
- Random Forest Regressor
- XGBoost (primary model)

**Classification** — predicts complexity tier (low / mid / high / extreme)
- Logistic Regression
- Decision Tree
- Support Vector Machine (SVM)

**Clustering & Dimensionality Reduction** — discovers natural asset groupings
- K-Means Clustering
- PCA (2D and 3D visualization)

**Optional — Graph Neural Networks**
- PyTorch Geometric GNN treating mesh as vertex/edge graph
- Captures structural topology beyond scalar statistics

**Evaluation metrics:**
- Regression: MAE, RMSE, MAPE, R²
- Classification: Accuracy, F1-score, confusion matrix
- Explainability: SHAP feature importance plots

---

## Complexity Tiers

| Tier | Face Count |
|---|---|
| Low | < 10,000 |
| Mid | 10,000 – 100,000 |
| High | 100,000 – 1,000,000 |
| Extreme | > 1,000,000 |

---

## Dataset Sources

Assets collected from:
- [Sketchfab](https://sketchfab.com/features/free-3d-models) — CC0 and CC-BY licensed models
- [ShapeNet](https://shapenet.org) — large-scale categorized 3D model repository
- [Poly Haven](https://polyhaven.com/models) — CC0 production-quality assets
- [Blender Studio Open Movies](https://studio.blender.org/films) — production-grade `.blend` scenes
- [PBRT v4 Scenes](https://github.com/mmp/pbrt-v4-scenes) — path-tracer benchmark scenes
- [Stanford 3D Scanning Repository](https://graphics.stanford.edu/data/3Dscanrep) — classic research meshes

